# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 16-inch-softball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:16-inch-softball/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 has been a basketball format long played in streets and gyms across the world, albeit in a less formal way.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Starting in the late 2000s, 3x3 game rules started to become standardized throughout the United States, most notably through the Gus Macker and Hoop It Up tournament series, which held large events across the country that included teams and players from all skill levels.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] In 1992, Adidas launched its now-discontinued streetball competition.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Since then, the number of 3x3 events and competitions has been steadily growing around the world.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] A Romanian organization, Sport Arena Streetball, began hosting 3x3 events in Bucharest as early as 2005, helping to grow the sport locally and regionally before formal FIBA rules were introduced.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] FIBA first test 3x3 at the 2007 Asian Indoor Games in Macau, followed by further test events in April 2008 in the Dominican Republic and October 2008 in Indonesia.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The international debut of 3x3 under FIBA rules occurred at the 2009 Asian Youth Games, where 19 teams competed in the boys' tournament and 16 teams competed in the girls' tournament, with all games held at Anglican High School in Tanah Merah, Singapore.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 made its worldwide competitive debut at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics in Singapore, where 20 teams competed in both boys' and girls' categories, with games held at the Youth Space.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Since then, FIBA has regularly held world championships in both open and U18 categories.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Bucharest, later called the "Mecca of 3x3 basketball" by Sports Illustrated, hosted the first FIBA Europe 3x3 Championships in 2014, an event that helped establish organized 3x3 competition across Europe.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] In subsequent years, the city also hosted international 3x3 tournaments, attracting teams from outside Europe.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] FIBA developed 3x3 as a standalone discipline with its own format and regular international competitions.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made its Olympic debut at the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The 3x3 basketball variation has also been used in several tournaments, such as the Nike 3ON3 Tournament and Spokane Hoopfest, the largest 3x3 basketball tournament in the world, held annually in Spokane, Washington.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] FIBA releases from time-to-time a supplement to its official basketball rules specifically for 3x3.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The rules state that regular FIBA rules apply to all situations not specifically addressed in the FIBA 3x3 rules.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The current set, both in an abbreviated version and longer format, was published in August 2019.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The current rules depart from regular full-court basketball in the following ways.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Each team consists of three players and one substitute.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Each team must have three players on the court when the game begins.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The game is played on a half-court with one basket.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The American NBA & WNBA standard half-court distance is 15.24 m (50 ft) wide & 14.33 m (47 ft) long.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The ball is the size of a size 6 basketball (720 mm, 28.5 in) as used in the women's full-court game and its mass is that of the size 7 standard (620 g, 22 oz) used in the men's full-court game.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] A coin toss is held immediately before the game, and the winning team of the coin flip can choose to take possession of the ball at the start of the game, or take the first possession of a potential overtime period.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] In turn, this means that if the game goes into overtime, the first possession goes to the team that started the game on defense.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The game begins with the defensive team passing the ball to the offensive team to signify the start of the game.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] All offensive players must begin outside of the arc (the opposite side of the arc of the net), and the defensive team must begin inside of the arc.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Once the offensive team receives the ball, the clock starts.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] This exchange is also used to restart the game from any dead ball situation.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The game is a single period of a maximum 10 minutes and the winner is the first team to score 21 or the team with the higher score at the end of the 10 minutes; scoring 21 points immediately ends the game.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Every successful shot inside the arc, including free throws, is awarded one point, while every successful shot outside of the arc ("downtown") is awarded two points.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] After a made goal or free throw (except for technical or unsportsmanlike fouls and team fouls 10 or more; see below), play restarts with a player from the non-scoring team taking the ball directly under the basket and then dribbling or passing it to a point behind the arc.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The defense is not allowed to play for the ball inside the block/charge semi-circle under the basket.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] In any held-ball situation, the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The offensive team must attempt a shot for a goal within 12 seconds.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] An offensive player may also not dribble inside the arc with their back or side to the basket for more than 3 consecutive seconds.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] For either violation the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] There is a Trent Tucker Rule in which with up to 0.2 seconds left in regulation or on the shot clock, a high lob, or tip-in must be made.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] A tie in regulation time leads to an untimed overtime period, after a one-minute intermission.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Whichever team began the game as the defensive team, begins overtime as the offensive team.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The first team to score two points wins the game.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Note: if a game is tied at 20 at the end of regulation, a team scoring their 21st point in overtime does not end the game.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Substitutions can occur only in a dead-ball situation; a substitute can only enter from behind the end line opposite the basket, and the substitution becomes official once the player leaving the game has "tagged up" by making physical contact with the substitute.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Each team is allowed one 30 second time-out per game.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Each personal or technical foul counts as one team foul, while each unsportsmanlike or disqualifying foul counts as two team fouls.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Personal fouls during the act of shooting inside the arc are awarded one free throw, while fouls during the act of shooting behind the arc and the shot is unsuccessful are awarded two free throws.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Team fouls 7, 8 and 9 are awarded two free throws, and all team fouls thereafter are awarded two free throws and possession of the ball.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The "bonus" rule specifically supersedes the normal rule for fouls in the act of shooting.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The un-timed overtime period is considered extension of regulation for purpose of team fouls.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The first unsportsmanlike foul against a player results in two free throws.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] A second unsportsmanlike foul, or a disqualifying foul, results in two free throws and possession.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] A player who commits two unsportsmanlike fouls is disqualified.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] A team loses the game by default if all of its players are disqualified.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] All technical fouls result in one free throw, with possession going to the team that was entitled to possession at that time.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] If a foul is committed that results in the non-fouling team retaining possession, i.e. a technical or "unsportsmanlike" foul, the non-fouling team will receive the exchange outside of the arc.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Offensive fouls, if not technical, unsportsmanlike, or disqualifying, never result in free throws, regardless of the number of team fouls.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] In the case of a double foul, no free throws are awarded to either team, regardless of team foul count or whether the double fouls were unsportsmanlike.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] FIBA sees 3x3 as a major vehicle for promotion of the game of basketball throughout the world.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] FIBA Secretary General and IOC member Patrick Baumann explained: "The 3x3 concept has all the elements and skills required for basketball, it has inspired and will continue to inspire many great players in the future.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] At the same time, it is the easiest and one of the most-effective ways to bring youngsters to basketball, keep them and promote our game.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] FIBA is pursuing a strategy to implement 3x3.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] FIBA has developed a digital community that acts as a repository for all FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events worldwide and offers all players an individual world ranking based on the points earned by players at FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Any event around the world can become FIBA-endorsed by using FIBA's freeware, EventMaker, to organise the event.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] All FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events are classified within an established competition hierarchy, thus forming an official competition network.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The pinnacle of this competition network is the FIBA 3x3 World Tour, which includes a series of World Tour Masters and one Final.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] A team can qualify for a World Tour Masters by playing in any of the designated World Tour qualifiers.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The North American National Basketball Association (NBA) has also embraced 3x3.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Since 2016, the NBA has held a summer series of tournaments known as "Dew NBA 3X", where local amateur players from around the US compete in regional events for cash prizes and a finals berth.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The men's and women's NBA 3X champions then advance to the USA Basketball national 3x3 championship to potentially represent their country internationally.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] These tournaments also include live music performances, 3-point shooting contests for fans, an *NBA 2K* eSports competition, and appearances from current NBA players.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The qualification system for the FIBA 3x3 World Cups for men and women differs radically from the system used for FIBA full-court competitions.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] According to *The New York Times*, 3x3 has "an unusual qualifying system designed to grow the sport all year long as much as find the best teams for the World Cup." National team entries are based strictly on a country's official 3x3 ranking.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The ranking system for national teams also considers individual player rankings.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] For example, the US women's team qualified for the 2018 World Cup while the men's team did not, even though the men were ranked higher than the women on the cutoff date.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Participating in a FIBA-sanctioned 3x3 event can earn ranking points; according to a FIBA executive, "Andorra has heavy participation every weekend." The current concentration of ranking events in Europe makes it more difficult for non-European nations, especially the US, to qualify.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The aforementioned FIBA executive, when asked about the prospect of the 2020 Olympic debut of 3x3 potentially lacking any participation from the US, admitted that "a lot of teams want to beat the US.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] After the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics, FIBA established a regular World Cup that always includes men and women competing simultaneously in open, U23 and U18 categories.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] World Cups are played every year, except in years when there are Youth Olympic Games or Olympic Games.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] The COVID-19 pandemic caused the cancellation of the 2020 event.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] Classification to the World Cup is based on the 3x3 Federation Ranking, which ranks all National Federations based on the 3x3 Individual World Ranking points of their top 100 nationals in the respective category (i.e. men, women, U23 men, U23 women, U18 men, and U18 women).
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball became a regular European Games contest since its introduction at the 2015 European Games in Baku, Azerbaijan.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made a debut in Olympic programme for the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo, Japan, for both men and women.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball was included in 2022 Commonwealth Games in Birmingham, England.
[src:16-inch-softball/3x3-basketball] After the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, FIBA banned Russian teams and officials from participating in FIBA 3x3 Basketball competitions.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A **501(c) organization** is a nonprofit organization in the federal law of the United States according to Internal Revenue Code (26 U.S.C. § 501(c)).
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Such organizations are exempt from some federal income taxes.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Sections 503 through 505 set out the requirements for obtaining such exemptions.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Many states refer to Section 501(c) for definitions of organizations exempt from state taxation as well.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] 501(c) organizations can receive unlimited contributions from individuals, corporations, and unions.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] For example, a nonprofit organization may be tax-exempt under section 501(c)(3) if its primary activities are charitable, religious, educational, scientific, literary, testing for public safety, fostering amateur sports competition, or preventing cruelty to children or animals.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] According to the IRS Publication 557, in the *Organization Reference Chart* section, the following is an exact list of 501(c) organization types (29 in total) and their corresponding descriptions.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A 501(c) organization is subject to tax on its unrelated business income.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] For most organizations, an organization's activity generates unrelated business income if it is regularly carried on and it is not substantially related to furthering the exempt purpose of the organization.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Disposal of donated goods valued over $2,500, or acceptance of goods worth over $5,000 may trigger special filing and record-keeping requirements.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A 501(c) organization must maintain proper records and file certain annual or special-purpose tax returns, e.g., 26 U.S.C. § 6033 and 26 U.S.C. § 6050L.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Prior to 2008, an annual return was not generally required from an exempt organization with less than $25,000 in gross income yearly.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Since 2008, most organizations whose annual gross receipts are less than $50,000 must file an annual information return known as Form 990-N.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Form 990-N, Form 990, Form 990-EZ, and Form 990-PF must be submitted electronically.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Failure to file required returns such as Form 990 (Return of Organization Exempt From Income Tax) may result in fines of up to $250,000 per year.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Exempt or political organizations, excluding churches or similar religious entities, must make their returns, reports, notices, and exempt applications available for public inspection.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Form 4506-A also allows the public inspection or photocopying access to Form 1023 "Application for Recognition of Exemption" or Form 1024, Form 8871 "Political Organization Notice of Section 527 Status", and Form 8872 "Political Organization Report of Contribution and Expenditures".
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Internet access to many organizations' 990 and some other forms are available through GuideStar.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Failure to file such timely returns and to make other specific information available to the public also is prohibited.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Between 2010 and 2017 the IRS revoked the nonprofit status of more than 760,000 nonprofit organizations for failing to file the 990 form.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The 501(c)(3) exemption also applies for any unincorporated community chest, fund, cooperating association, or foundation that is organized and operated exclusively for those purposes.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] There are also supporting organizations—often referred to in shorthand form as "Friends of" organizations.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] 26 U.S.C. § 170, provides a deduction, for federal income tax purposes, for some donors who make charitable contributions to most types of 501(c)(3) organizations, among others.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Organizations described in section 501(c)(3) are prohibited from conducting political campaign activities to intervene in elections to public office.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] On the other hand, public charities (but not private foundations) may conduct a limited amount of lobbying to influence legislation.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Although the law states that "No substantial part..." of a public charity's activities can go to lobbying, charities may register for a 501(h) election allowing them to lawfully conduct lobbying activities as long as their financial expenditure does not exceed a specified amount.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] 501(c)(3) organizations risk loss of tax exempt status if any of these rules are violated.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to conduct some or all of its charitable activities outside the United States.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Donors' contributions to a 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible only if the contribution is for the use of the 501(c)(3) organization, and that the 501(c)(3) organization is not merely serving as an agent or conduit of a foreign charitable organization.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Additional procedures are required of 501(c)(3) organizations that are private foundations.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A **501(c)(4) organization** is a social welfare organization, such as a civic organization or a neighborhood association.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] An organization is considered by the IRS to be operated exclusively for the promotion of social welfare if it is primarily engaged in promoting the common good and general welfare of the people of the community.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Net earnings must be exclusively used for charitable, educational, or recreational purposes.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] 501(c)(4)s are similar to 501(c)(5)s and 501(c)(6)s in that the organizations may inform the public on controversial subjects and attempt to influence legislation relevant to its program.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Unlike 501(c)(3) organizations, they may also participate in political campaigns and elections, as long as their primary activity is the promotion of social welfare and related to the organization's purpose.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The income tax exemption for 501(c)(4) organizations applies to most of their operations, but income spent on political activities—generally the advocacy of a particular candidate in an election—is taxable.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] An "action" organization generally qualifies as a 501(c)(4) organization.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] An "action" organization is one whose activities substantially include, or are exclusively, direct or grassroots lobbying related to advocacy for or against legislation or proposing, supporting, or opposing legislation that is related to its purpose.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A 501(c)(4) organization may directly or indirectly support or oppose a candidate for public office as long as such activities are not a substantial amount of its activities.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A 501(c)(4) organization that lobbies must register with the Clerk of the House if it lobbies members of the House or their staff.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Likewise, a 501(c)(4) organization must register with the Secretary of the Senate if it lobbies members of the Senate or their staff.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] In addition, the 501(c)(4) organization must either inform its members the amount it spends on lobbying or pay a proxy tax to the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Lobbying expenses and political expenses are not deductible as business expenses.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Wisconsin Right to Life, Inc.*, in which the Supreme Court struck down the part of the McCain-Feingold Act that prohibited 501(c)(4)s, 501(c)(5)s, and 501(c)(6)s from broadcasting electioneering communications.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The Act defined an electioneering communication as a communication that mentions a candidate's name 60 days before a primary or 30 days before a general election.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Contributions to 501(c)(4) organizations are not tax-deductible as charitable donations unless the organization is either a volunteer fire department or a veterans organization.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Dues or contributions to 501(c)(4) organizations may be deductible as a business expense under IRC 162, although amounts paid for intervention or participation in any political campaign, direct lobbying, grass roots lobbying, and contact with certain federal officials are not deductible.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] If a 501(c)(4) engages in a substantial number of these activities, then only the amount of dues or contributions that can be attributed to other activities may be deductible as a business expense.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The organization must provide a notice to its members containing a reasonable estimate of the amount related to lobbying and political campaign expenditures, or else it is subject to a proxy tax on its lobbying and political campaign expenditures.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] It must also state that contributions to the organization are not deductible as charitable contributions during fundraising.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A 501(c)(4) organization is not required to disclose their donors publicly, with the exception of organizations that make independent expenditures as of 2018.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The former complete lack of disclosure led to extensive use of the 501(c)(4) provisions for organizations that are actively involved in lobbying, and has become controversial.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Criticized as "dark money", spending from these organizations on political advertisements has exceeded spending from Super PACs.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Spending by organizations that do not disclose their donors increased from less than $5.2 million in 2006 to well over $300 million during the 2012 election season.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The origins of 501(c)(4) organizations date back to the Revenue Act of 1913, which created a new group of tax-exempt organizations dedicated to social welfare in a precursor to what is now Internal Revenue Code Section 501(c)(4).
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The Protecting Americans from Tax Hikes Act of 2015 introduced a new requirement on 501(c)(4) organizations.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Within 60 days of the organization's formation, a 501(c)(4) organization is required to file Form 8976 with the Internal Revenue Service as notification that it is operating as a section 501(c)(4) organization.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The Internal Revenue Service will acknowledge receipt of the notification, but the acknowledgment is not a determination that the organization qualifies for section 501(c)(4) tax-exempt status.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A 501(c)(4) organization is not required to send the notification if the organization was formed on or before July 8, 2016, and it either applied for a determination letter using Form 1024 or filed a Form 990 between December 19, 2015, and July 8, 2016.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] As of January 2018, the application for recognition of exemption as a 501(c)(4) organization is a new form, Form 1024-A, rather than Form 1024.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] In 2017 revocations of 501(c)(4) groups comprised 58% which usually is only 15% of the total nonprofits which have their tax status revoked by the IRS for their failure to file Form 990.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A **501(c)(5) organization** is a labor organization, an agricultural organization, or a horticultural organization.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Labor unions, county fairs, and flower societies are examples of these types of groups.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Labor union organizations were a primary benefactor of this organization type, dating to the 19th century.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] According to the Internal Revenue Service, a 501(c)(5) organization has a duty of providing service to its members first.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The organization's benefits may not inure to a specific member, but the rules for inurement vary among the three different types of organizations under this segment.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A 501(c)(5) organization can make unlimited corporate, individual, or union contributions.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A labor organization may pay benefits to its members because paying benefits improves all members' shared working conditions.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] An agricultural organization can provide financial assistance to its members in order to improve the conditions of those engaged in agricultural pursuits generally.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Members can benefit in incidental ways from the organization's exempt activities as long as the benefits are available to all persons.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The first exemption for labor organizations from corporate income tax was enacted as part of the Payne–Aldrich Tariff Act of 1909.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The Revenue Act of 1913 excluded "labor, agricultural, or horticultural organizations" from income tax liability.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Much like 501(c)(4) and 501(c)(6) organizations, 501(c)(5) organizations may also perform some political activities.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] 501(c)(5) organizations are allowed to attempt to influence legislation that is related to the common union interests of its members.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] 501(c)(5) organizations can receive unlimited contributions from corporations, individuals, and labor unions.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The names and addresses of contributors are not required to be made available for public inspection.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] All other information, including the amount of contributions, the description of noncash contributions, and any other information, is required to be made available for public inspection unless it clearly identifies the contributor.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A union membership dues paid to a 501(c)(5) organization are generally an ordinary and necessary business expense.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The membership dues are tax-deductible in full unless a substantial part of the 501(c)(5) organization's activities consists of political activity, in which case a tax deduction is allowed only for the portion of membership dues that are for other activities.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The Federal Election Commission is required to enforce this provision based on a federal court decision in 2018.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A **501(c)(6) organization** is a business league, a chamber of commerce like the U.S.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A business league may qualify if it is an association of persons having a common business interest, whose purpose is to promote the common business interest and whose activities improve business conditions rather than actually conduct the business itself.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Members of the organization must be of the same trade, business, occupation, or profession in order to qualify.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A local chamber of commerce or board of trade could qualify for similar reasons except that they may promote the common economic interests of all the commercial enterprises in a given trade or community.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] In order to qualify for a tax-exemption under section 501(c)(6), the organization must specify that it seeks to promote and improve business condition for a specific type of business.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Improving business conditions for *all* types of businesses is not generally qualifying.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Similarly, providing a service for a specific type of business is also not typically qualifying, as that would usually be more of a commercial enterprise.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] For example, the service of managing health insurance plans for its member businesses is often a commercial enterprise if it is not substantially related to improving the business conditions for specific lines of businesses.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] An association that promotes the common interests of certain hobbyists would not qualify because the Internal Revenue Service does not consider hobbies to be activities conducted as businesses.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] An organization whose primary activity is advertising the products or services of its members does not qualify because the organization is performing a service for its members rather than promoting common interests.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] If an organization's primary activity is advertising the products or services of its members' industry as a whole, however, the organization will generally qualify if it also performs other services for its members.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Much like 501(c)(4) and 501(c)(5) organizations, 501(c)(6) organizations may also perform some political activities.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] 501(c)(6) organizations are allowed to attempt to influence legislation that is related to the common business interests of its members.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A 501(c)(6) organization may receive unlimited contributions from corporations, individuals, and labor unions.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The names and addresses of contributors are not required to be made available for public inspection, with the exception of a 501(c)(6) organization that makes independent expenditures.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] All other information, including the amount of contributions, the description of non-cash contributions, and any other information, is required to be made available for public inspection unless it clearly identifies the contributor.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Chamber of Commerce is a large political spender, and Freedom Partners used its status as a 501(c)(6) organization to raise and distribute over $250 million during the 2012 election campaigns without disclosing its donors.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The group's existence was not publicly known until nearly a year after the election.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A business's membership dues paid to a 501(c)(6) organization are generally an ordinary and necessary business expense.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The membership dues are tax-deductible in full unless a substantial part of the 501(c)(6) organization's activities consists of political activity, in which case a tax deduction is allowed only for the portion of membership dues that are for other activities.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The predecessor of IRC 501(c)(6) was enacted as part of the Revenue Act of 1913 likely due to a U.S.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Chamber of Commerce request for an exemption for nonprofit "civic" and "commercial" organizations, which resulted in IRC 501(c)(4) for nonprofit "civic" organizations and IRC 501(c)(6) for nonprofit "commercially-oriented" organizations.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The Revenue Act of 1928 amended the statute to include real estate boards.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] In 1966, professional football leagues were added to the described organizations.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] IRC 501(c)(6) amendment was enacted in 1966 to ensure that a professional football league's exemption would not be jeopardized because it administered a players' pension fund.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Additionally, a professional sports league's exemption is not to be jeopardized because its primary source of revenue is the sale of television broadcasting rights to its games because the broadcasting of games increases public awareness of the sport.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] In 2013, Senator Tom Coburn introduced legislation to disallow a tax exemption for the National Football League, the Professional Golfers' Association of America, and other professional sports organizations.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Coburn estimated the tax exemption cost $100 million, but he said he could not get other members of Congress to support the legislation.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A **501(c)(7) organization** is a social or recreational club that is organized for pleasure, recreation, and other nonprofitable purposes.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Members must share interests and have a common goal directed toward pleasure and recreation, and the organization must provide opportunities for personal contact among members.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The organization's facilities and services must be open to its members and their guests only.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The organization must be a club of individuals, and no individual may derive profit from the organization's net earnings.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Examples include college alumni associations; college fraternities or college sororities operating chapter houses for students; country clubs; amateur sport clubs; supper clubs that provide a meeting place, library, and dining room for members; hobby clubs; and garden clubs.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A substantial amount of the 501(c)(7) organization's activities must be related to social and recreational activities for its members.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] No more than 35 percent of its gross receipts may derive from non-members, and no more than 15 percent of its gross receipts is permitted to come from use of its facilities or services by the general public.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] An organization that exceeds these limits may lose its 501(c)(7) status.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Similarly, if at least 75 percent of a group using club facilities are members of the organization, the Internal Revenue Service will assume the nonmembers are the guests of the member, and the revenue is deemed to be derived from the member.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] It is the responsibility of the organization to maintain these records.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] If the organization does not keep sufficient records to link revenue to a member, the Internal Revenue Service assumes the revenue came from a nonmember.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The organization is subject to Unrelated Business Income Tax for the revenue derived from nonmember use of its facilities and services, less allowable deductions.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] If the organization sells assets that were previously used for recreational or social purposes, the proceeds are considered related business income as long as the proceeds are reinvested in the organization.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Public use of the organization's facilities must be minimal, generally either less than $2,500 per year or less than five percent of its total gross receipts from normal and usual activities of the club.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A 501(c)(7) organization cannot have a written policy of discriminating on the basis of race, color, or religion.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Nevertheless, a 501(c)(7) organization is permitted to limit its members to a particular religion in order to further the teachings of that religion.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] An auxiliary of a 501(c)(8) fraternal benefit society that limits membership to members of a particular religion is allowed to do so as well.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Having written policies that limit its membership by ethnic origin and gender would not jeopardize the organization's tax-exempt status.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Congress justified the tax-exemption with the reasoning that the members join to provide themselves with recreational or social organization without further tax consequences, similar as if they had paid for the benefits directly.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Tax-exemption was available for organizations operated exclusively for pleasure, recreation, and other nonprofitable purposes.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] In 1969, Congress passed a law stating that social and recreational clubs were permitted to engage in some unrelated business income, subject to income tax.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A **501(c)(8) organization** is a fraternal benefit society.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The society must have members of a similar calling, recreation, or profession, or members who work together to accomplish a worthy goal.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The members have associated themselves in order to help each other and to promote the common cause.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The society must have written documentation of its eligibility standards for membership, classes of membership, a process of admission, and rights and privileges of members.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The members must have a common bond, which may be based on religious beliefs, gender, occupation, ethnicity, or shared values.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The society must have a supreme governing body and subordinate lodges into which members are elected, initiated, or admitted in accordance with its laws.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The supreme governing body should be composed of delegates elected directly by members or intermediate assemblies.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The society must offer benefits to members, which may include life insurance, medical insurance, scholarships, educational programs, travel opportunities, and discount programs.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Revenue generated from providing benefits to non-members must be insubstantial to the society and may be taxable as unrelated business income.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Fraternal benefit societies trace their lineage back through mutual benefit societies, friendly societies and eventually to medieval guilds.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Many fraternal benefit societies were founded to serve the needs of immigrants and other under-served groups who shared common bonds of religion, ethnicity, gender, occupation or shared values.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Section 38 of the Payne–Aldrich Tariff Act of 1909 was the first law to provide a tax-exemption for fraternal beneficiary societies.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The tax-exemption was later codified as section 501(c)(8) with the Internal Revenue Code of 1954.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Similar to 501(c)(8) organizations, 501(c)(10) organizations are also fraternal societies, orders, or associations operating under the lodge system, but 501(c)(10) organizations do not offer life, sick, accident, or other benefits.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] 501(c)(10) organizations devote net earnings exclusively to religious, charitable, scientific, literary, educational, and fraternal purposes.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A **501(c)(13)** organization is a certain type of cemetery company.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] There are two primary types of eligible cemetery companies.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A mutual cemetery company must be either "owned by and operated exclusively for the benefit of its lot owners who hold such lots for bona fide burial purposes and not for the purpose of resale" or engages in the burial of impoverished people performing similar charitable activities.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A nonprofit cemetery corporation must be incorporated solely for the purpose of the burial or the cremation of bodies and no part of its net earnings inures to the benefit of any private shareholder or individual.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Any net gain by the cemetery must be devoted to certain cemetery functions, such as the cemetery's operations, maintenance, and improvements; acquisition of cemetery property; and investment of the net gain in order to provide additional income for cemetery functions.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Net gains are not allowed to be distributed to individuals.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A perpetual care fund that is used by a profit-making cemetery to maintain cemetery properties and burial lots is not eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] On the other hand, a nonprofit organization may have a perpetual care fund without jeopardizing its exemption under Section 501(c)(13).
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A cemetery that owns or operates a morgue, whether on its own grounds or elsewhere, is not eligible under 501(c)(13) because the Internal Revenue Service does not consider mortuary services necessarily incident to burial purposes.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The provision of traditional burial services that directly support and maintain basic tenets and beliefs of a religion regarding burial of its members" may still be eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A cemetery that buries animals is not eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] A cemetery company wishing to be recognized under Section 501(c)(13) needs to prepare and file Form 1024 with the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Charitable contributions to a 501(c)(13) organization are tax-deductible to the donor.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Payments for perpetual care of a particular lot or a particular crypt are not considered tax-deductible charitable contributions.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Payments made as part of the purchase price of a burial lot or crypt are not considered tax-deductible charitable contributions, even if a portion of the payment is for the perpetual care of the entirety of the cemetery.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Bequests or gifts to a 501(c)(13) cemetery are not deductible for federal estate tax purposes or gift tax purposes.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] Historically, cemeteries were exempt from local property taxes and excise taxes in most states because states generally considered cemeteries to be performing a recognized civic service.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] The Tariff Act of 1913 provided an exemption from federal income taxes for mutual cemetery companies that were organized and operated exclusively "for the benefit of their members".
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] In 1921, Congress extended the tax-exemption to cemetery companies that are not mutual and to cemetery companies that are not operated for profit as well as any corporation solely incorporated to operate a cemetery and whose net gains do not inure to any person.
[src:16-inch-softball/501-c] In 1970, Congress added crematorium in the definition of cemetery for the purposes of Section 501(c)(13).
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] In Chicago, Daniel "Danny" Martin and Bernard "Bernie" Litko, two friends and colleagues in their twenties, discuss their sexual escapades.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] Later, their recreational softball team, sponsored by local bar Mother's, plays against a local advertising agency in Grant Park and wins.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] Attending this game with her girlfriends is Deborah "Debbie" Sullivan, who works at the advertising company and is having an affair with her boss, Steve Carlson.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] Debbie catches Danny's eye and they flirt by the beer keg.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] She and her friends, Joan and Pat, attend the game's afterparty at Mother's, where Debbie again runs into Danny, with whom Pat flirts and to whom Joan takes an immediate dislike.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] Danny and Debbie wind up back at his apartment and have sex, after which she hastily leaves.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] The next day, Danny calls Debbie at work "about last night", and asks her out on a second date, which she accepts.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] Afterwards, they again end up in bed together and spend the following day exploring the city, whereupon Danny reveals to Debbie that his dream is to quit his job at a restaurant supply company and open his own restaurant.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] They begin dating more seriously and move in together, heavily disappointing Joan and Bernie, who dislike each other as well.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] As neither has ever been in a serious relationship before, they attempt to navigate cohabitation without much support from their friends.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] Despite having told each other the "L word", Danny and Debbie's relationship becomes strained.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] It reaches a boiling point at a New Year's Eve party at Mother's, where Debbie witnesses a drunken Pat making advances towards Danny, and Joan discovers her boyfriend is married and returning to his wife.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] Joan tearfully asks Debbie to take her home, to which she agrees, despite Danny's drunken objections.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] Upon Debbie's return home, Danny expresses his unhappiness and ends their relationship.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] Debbie immediately moves out of their apartment and back in with Joan.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] Danny and Debbie both date other people, but he begins to regret their breakup.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] Some time later, Danny calls Debbie at work asking for another chance, but she rebuffs him and hangs up on him.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] Patrick's Day celebration at Mother's, Danny tells Debbie he made a mistake and still loves her; she insists she has moved on and their relationship is over.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] Hoping to move on with his life, Danny partners with Gus to revitalize the Swallow into an old-school diner, achieving his dream.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] That summer, at another softball game, Danny and Bernie see Debbie riding her bicycle through the park with Joan, who encourages her to talk to Danny.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] She approaches him and they both express regret at how their relationship turned out.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] As Debbie begins to turn away, Danny asks her out again and suggests they go to a great new place, but she suggests with a smile that they just go to "some old joint", signifying that she is aware of his new restaurant.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] As she rides away on her bicycle, Bernie convinces Danny to run after her, and the camera pans out to see Danny and Debbie passing through the park.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] At one point, Bill Murray and Nick Nolte were attached to appear in the film as the lead and supporting role respectively.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] A "disastrous meeting" between them caused both of them to turn down the film.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] The film was a box office success, grossing $38,702,310 domestically.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] It was the 26th highest-grossing film of 1986 in the United States, and the 10th highest-grossing R-rated film of 1986.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] On the review aggregator website Rotten Tomatoes, the film holds an approval rating of 65% based on 31 reviews, with an average rating of 6.3/10.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] Audiences surveyed by CinemaScore gave the film a grade "A−" on scale of A to F.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] Last summer's movie made them look stupid and shallow.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] *About Last Night . . .* gives them the best acting opportunities either one has ever had, and they make the most of them." Sheila Benson of the *Los Angeles Times* called it "[t]ender, marvelously well played (by almost everyone) and thoroughly engaging.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] The film's soundtrack album was released on EMI America Records.
[src:16-inch-softball/about-last-night-1986-film] The album includes music by Sheena Easton, Michael Henderson, John Oates, Jermaine Jackson, John Waite, Paul Davis, and Bob Seger.
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] The AFL held two official Australian Football League (AFL) pre-season AFLX competitions featuring senior AFL clubs and players, in 2018 and 2019, but these were unpopular with spectators and did not return in 2020.
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] The variation continues to be promoted by the AFL Commission as a participation sport in development regions and areas, and particularly where full-sized cricket grounds are not available.
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] Since the COVID-19 pandemic, AFLX has been merged with AFL 9s and retained only the X brand, co-branding AFL 9s as Junior X, Youth X and Senior X and aligning it with the more widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] The rules of the game differed from standard Australian rules football in some significant ways.
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] The game was played on a rectangular soccer-sized pitch, allowing matches to be hosted by stadiums that usually lacked the suitable field dimensions for Australian rules football.
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] AFLX was first trialled at Arden Street Oval in January 2017.
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] Two months later, it was trialed at was first trialled on a soccer pitch at Lakeside Stadium in a match between the Port Melbourne Football Club and Coburg Football Club.
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] AFLX pre-season competition was launched by AFL chief executive officer Gillon McLachlan at Docklands Stadium on 6 February 2018.
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] McLachlan said that AFLX would help promote football internationally.
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] The 2018 competition attracted more than 40,000 fans to tournaments in Adelaide, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] In Melbourne, TV ratings were reported as "modest" by AFL standards, with the three events drawing an average five-city metro audience of over 120,000 on Channel Seven's secondary channels.
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] The AFL made several rule tweaks midway through the second season in attempt to make it higher scoring by inflating the scoring points for behinds from 1 to 2, goals from 6 to 12 and Super Goals from 10 to 20.
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] Whitten Legends Game was also played under "EJX" (modified version of AFLX named after E J Whitten) at AAMI Park in Melbourne.
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] It attracted just 6,000 spectators, the lowest in the series history.
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] AFLX did not return as a senior AFL competition in 2020, as AFL had a greater focus on AFLW.
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] Post the COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased the number of players to 9, effectively merging AFLX with AFL 9s and aligning with the widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] The reception to the two AFL pre-season competitions among fans and the media was mostly poor, with ABC Radio Grandstand journalist Richard Hinds being particularly savage in labelling it a "hollow, unappealing, pressure-free, atmosphere-deficient, oval-in-a-rectangle hole yawn-fest".
[src:16-inch-softball/aflx] Con Stavros of RMIT's school of Economics, Finance and Marketing, expressed doubts about the potential of AFLX to export Australian rules football but acknowledged that using rectangular playing fields instead of the standard cricket ones would make such expansion easier.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Although similar to paintball in concept and gameplay, airsoft pellets do not leave visible dye markings on their target and hits are not always apparent, though the pellets can sometimes leave small bruises or welts on exposed skin (and so protective gear is still recommended).
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The game therefore relies heavily on an honor system in which players who have been hit are expected to call themselves out of play in keeping with honesty, fairness and sportsmanship.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The airsoft guns used are mostly magazine-fed, with some having manual/battery motor-powered spring-piston pump power plants similar to Nerf Blasters, or pneumatically powered by replaceable compressed gas (e.g. propane ("green gas"), 1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane or CO2) canisters.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Many airsoft guns also have mounting platforms compatible with genuine firearm accessories, and most cosmetically resemble real firearms.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] This makes them popular for military simulation and historical reenactments.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] There are also professional gun safety and weapon manipulation training conducted with airsoft in some fields, such as law enforcement training, due to better safety and lower cost.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The United States Coast Guard, for instance, officially adopted airsoft for training in 2018.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Airsoft gameplay varies in style and composition, but often ranges from action shooting to short organized live action role-playing (LARP) scenarios, close quarters battle skirmishes, military simulations (MilSim) or historical reenactments.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] It is played in indoor courses or outdoor fields.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Combat situations on the field may involve the use of genuine military tactics to achieve objectives set in each game.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Participants may attempt to emulate the tactical equipment and accessories used by modern military and police organizations.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] A game is normally kept safe by trained professionals acting as supervisors and marshals.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Before gameplay, an airsoft gun's muzzle velocity is usually checked through a chronograph and usually measured in feet per second (FPS) or joules, a measurement for kinetic energy.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Some countries have a set velocity or muzzle energy restriction; guns shooting over the legal muzzle velocity can be confiscated.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Some playing fields further restrict minimum engagement distances, requiring players to yell "Bang Bang!" or other verbal phrases in order to prevent shooting other players at close distances, which may cause injury.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] In certain countries use of laser sights of any kind is illegal, including gun scopes with integrated lasers.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Airsoft originated in postwar Japan during the early 1970s, when photographer Ichiro Nagata, an avid shooting enthusiast himself, thought about making modelguns that shoot real projectiles that could not kill or wound.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Early airsoft guns use a manual spring-piston design and are essentially single-shot, tailoring to the needs of shooting enthusiasts while conforming to Japan's strict weapons control laws.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Originally designed for target shooting, the plastic balls used in these "guns" can be shot at humans without causing injury due to the low muzzle energy.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] These new-generation replica guns were trademarked as **soft air guns** because the refrigerant propellant used was significantly weaker ("soft") than the canistered CO2 used in proper airguns (pellet guns and BB guns).
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] This practical convenience of AEGs led soft air guns to quickly become popular for casual MilSim games, which the Japanese call **survival games** (サバイバルゲーム, *sabaibaru gēmu*).
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Asahi Firearms was also a model company from Japan who operated in the 1980s and 90s and was one of the early pioneers of the airsoft hobby.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Airsoft guns spread to the United Kingdom in the late 1980s and early 1990s via a company called LS.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] They were sold in separate pieces and had to be assembled out-of-box before they were capable of shooting.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] These then became available to the rest of Europe and North America and rapidly gained popularity worldwide.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Since the mid-1980s, airsoft has been adapted with a purely recreational application in mind, and the sport is enjoyed by all ages.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Airsoft replicas are produced globally, with the majority being manufactured in East Asia.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Many law enforcement agencies and military units within the United States now start using airsoft for force-on-force tactical training drills.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The guns used in airsoft are typically classified as imitation firearms.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] They have a mechanism for shooting projectiles 6 mm, 6.4 mm, or 8 mm in diameter.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Some companies produce full replicas of counterpart grenade launchers which fire a projectile spray of 6 millimetres (0.24 in) pellets by use of a high-powered spring mechanism or a compressed gas propellant (i.e. green gas, propane, compressed air, or CO2).
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] There is also a type of airsoft gun that is powered by a single (HPA) high-pressure air tank and a battery pack to power the internal FCU "Fire Control Unit" computer board.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] These guns are often known for their high and adjustable RPS or "Rounds Per Second" and durability.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] These HPA replicas are most often referred to as "PolarStars", although this refers to a popular brand of HPA engines and accessories.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] A typical airsoft gun is noticeably lighter than its "real steel" counterpart due to the use of aluminum alloy and plastic materials, though some have added weights in them for a more realistic feel.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Japan has specific rules about producing airsoft guns with metal parts, while newer guns, especially those made in Taiwan and Mainland China, have both internal and external parts that are metallic.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Smoke caps, as well as noise amplifiers, are available for certain airsoft guns to add realism.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Gas handgun magazines usually contain 10 to 30 pellets in a standard-capacity magazine; however, some are high-capacity magazines and can hold 50 rounds or more.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] In the case of AEG rifles, magazines come in either real-capacity (equivalent to the 30-round capacity of its real steel counterpart), low-capacity (10–50 rounds), mid-capacity (75–250 rounds), or high-capacity (250+ rounds).
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] These magazines have spring followers like in BB guns.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The high-cap magazines often have a ratchet wheel that can be wound up periodically to force pellets up from the holding chamber of the magazine to the feeding chute.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Due to loose pellets in the reservoir, they often make a rattling noise when running or walking.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Some airsoft guns have a battery-powered box or drum magazine that holds thousands of pellets, but these are usually only used and allowed on LMGs (light machine gun) type replicas.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] It is common for owners to "tech" (modify) their guns.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The majority of gearboxes are made to Tokyo Marui specifications and have aftermarket upgrade parts available commercially.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Some gearboxes are proprietary in design.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] It is also possible to perform DIY modifications.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The "hop-up" system, which is installed in most stock airsoft rifles and pistols, is used to increase effective ranges by putting backspin on the pellets.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The Magnus effect causes the pellets to experience more lift as they are shot, counteracting against gravity.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] A small rubber nub protrudes into the top of the barrel through a small hole, applies pressure on a rubber bucking, and catches the top of the pellet as it moves past.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Adjusting the hop-up makes the nub more or less protrude into the bucking, so that backspin is increased or reduced.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Ideally, the hop-up should be adjusted so that the pellets fly as far as possible in a straight line without curving upward too far or dropping too quickly.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Hop-Up does decrease the muzzle velocity (a gun firing 340 ft/s (100 m/s) with the hop fully unwound can drop to as low as 300 ft/s (91 m/s)).
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Ease and location of adjustment vary by gun design; some equipment provides a control that can be adjusted quickly during gameplay, while others may require partial disassembly.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] For example, a common location for Hop-Up adjustment is where the ejection port would be on a real firearm, which allows the machine to be covered while still allowing quick access to adjust the Hop-Up.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Some players customize their airsoft guns, either to improve performance or for purely aesthetic reasons.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Additions include scopes, fore-grips, and flashlights, red dot sights being the most commonly used.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Red dot sights are used to help aim, fore-grips are used to get a better grip on the airsoft gun, and flashlights (whether mounted or held in another hand) are used to illuminate dark areas and/or to blind opponents.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Even though in certain countries lasers are illegal, they are popular attachments in the U.S. and Europe.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Also available are "mock suppressors/silencers".
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] These resemble the actual firearm accessory that dampens sound.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Since Airsoft does not use combustibles for propulsion these usually serve no function.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Although there are models that function to "light up" a glow-in-the-dark BB using UV light similar to a tracer round.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Most airsoft guns fire round plastic pellets, usually white, but Tracers are common as well.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The pellets mostly range from 0.12 to 0.48 g.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] However, the most popular weights for AEGs (automatic electric guns) and GBB* (Gas Blow-Back guns) are 0.20 g to 0.32 g (whose muzzle velocity ranges from approximately 250 ft/s (76 m/s) to 400 ft/s (120 m/s)).
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Heavier rounds (0.36–0.40 g) are typically used in long-range and sniper applications since they are more stable in flight and less easily deflected by wind.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The pellets, which are called BBs (ball bearings), are usually bought in bags or bottles of 2,000 to 5,000, but other sizes are available, such as a 250,000 round (65 kg) package of tournament grade BBs.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Biodegradable BBs are a fraction more expensive than non-bio counterparts, but many fields require them.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] BBs are typically 5.95mm ±0.01 mm in diameter.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Due to the low muzzle energy (less than 1.5 J or 1.1 ft⋅lb even for high-power models) and poor sectional density, the pain an airsoft pellet causes on skin impact is about the same as getting pinched.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] As a reference value, a standard 0.20 gram 6 mm pellet, which is the most common size and weight, traveling at 100 m/s (330 ft/s) has 1 J (0.74 ft⋅lb) of kinetic energy.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Calculating the kinetic energy of an airsoft projectile is important for ensuring player safety.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] While a projectile’s ability to cause injury or penetrate a surface technically depends on energy density—that is, the kinetic energy divided by the impact area—this variable is nearly constant in airsoft, as most BBs have standardized diameters of 6 mm or 8 mm.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] As a result, the primary factor affecting the potential for injury or penetration is simply the kinetic energy of the BB.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Despite this, safety limits in airsoft are often expressed solely in FPS, which fails to account for variations in BB mass.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] where m is the mass in kilograms and v is the speed in meters per second.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Different regions vary in the velocity airsoft guns are allowed to shoot at.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] In the United States, velocity differs from the type of gameplay field.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Close Quarter Battle arenas typically regulate velocity on airsoft guns at around 110 m/s (350 ft/s).
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] For outdoor fields, velocity is usually regulated by the type of gun.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] With a standard 0.20 grams (3.1 gr) pellet, fully automatic Airsoft Electric Guns (AEGs) are often set at less than 120 m/s (400 ft/s), semi-automatic DMR-style AEGs at 120–140 m/s (400–450 ft/s), and bolt-action (manually cocked spring-piston) sniper rifles at 140–150 m/s (450–500 ft/s).
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The maximum effective range of field-legal airsoft guns is around 100 m (110 yd) with a highly upgraded sniper rifle replica.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Most airsoft guns used for field play will have an effective range of around 43–67 m (47–73 yd), depending on the intended gameplay role.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Most Airsoft guns are capable of shooting from 60 to 125 m/s (200 to 410 ft/s), although it is also possible to purchase upgraded internals that will enable the gun to shoot up to 170 m/s (550 ft/s) or higher.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] In California, a common limit for CQB is 110 m/s (350 ft/s).
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] In Ireland, Italy and Japan the muzzle energy limit for airsoft guns is 1 joule no matter what the type of gameplay.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] In the UK, the law allows weapons locked to semi-automatic and bolt-action rifles to fire up to 2.5 joules (at muzzle velocity up to 158 m/s or 518 ft/s).
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Any weapon "which is capable of discharging two or more missiles successively without repeated pressure on the trigger" is limited, by law, at 1.3 joules (velocity up to 114 m/s or 374 ft/s).
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Northern Ireland has a maximum velocity of 100 m/s (330 ft/s) with 0.20 g pellets, without regard to the type of equipment.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] In Sweden, the legal limitations of airsoft guns caps the energy limit at 10 joules for manual guns, and 3 joules for semi- and fully automatic guns.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The ballistics of spring- or electrically powered airsoft guns differ from real firearms in that a longer barrel will not always result in better accuracy.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The "sweet spot" for barrel length in a spring/electric powered airsoft gun is around 450 mm (18 in), beyond which added barrel length will not improve accuracy.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] In any case, barrel quality, velocity consistency, and hopup quality/design are more important factors with regard to accuracy.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Added barrel length will result in slightly increased velocity if the cylinder size and compression are appropriate for the barrel length.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] For example, a gun with a large cylinder and a long barrel will shoot slightly harder than a gun with a small cylinder and a short barrel (*ceteris paribus*).
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] This rule will apply even for barrels longer than 500 mm (20 in), if there is enough cylinder volume and air compression to propel the pellet through the barrel.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] However, the resulting velocity increase will be hardly noticeable.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The only considerable advantage of using a longer inner barrel in an AEG or spring-powered gun is that it generally will make the gun quieter due to the weakened muzzle pop.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] In gas-powered guns, added barrel length (to an appropriate extent) can result in increased velocity and accuracy to a degree.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Tighter-bore barrels will increase velocity because there will be less space between the pellet and the barrel for the air to escape through.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Most stock airsoft guns have 6.03–6.05 mm (0.237–0.238 in) bore barrels, but best performance is usually seen with "tightbore" barrels, which are 6.01–6.05 mm (0.237–0.238 in) in diameter.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] However, the tighter the bore, the more likely the chance of a pellet jam, and subsequently, tightbores need to be cleaned and lubricated regularly.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] It is generally agreed upon that a high-quality 6.01-6.02 mm barrel will provide the highest muzzle velocity, while a good-quality 6.03 mm or 6.05 mm barrel will provide the best compromise between power, accuracy and ease of maintenance.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The actual accuracy difference between tightbore sizes is debatable and usually outweighed by bore consistency.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Although, with the newfound popularity with HPA guns, the debate has been opened that barrels with a larger diameter (up to 6.13 mm or 0.241 in) could provide a more accurate shot.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Due to the higher volume of air surrounding the pellet it negates the chance of the pellet coming into contact with the barrel, throwing the pellet's trajectory off, similar to a musket, in how the bullet slams about before leaving the barrel.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Airsoft guns are not to be confused with BB guns, which are airguns that shoot 4.5 mm (.177 in) metallic spherical pellets, unlike the plastic pellets shot by airsoft guns.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Many manufacturers and retailers suggest treating an airsoft gun like a real gun at all times.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] This will help alleviate safety issues resulting in an accidental/negligent discharge, or prevent a public panic due to a carelessly displayed airsoft gun being mistaken for a real firearm.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Most manufacturers include an orange tip on the muzzle of the airsoft gun for signaling and safety purposes, and most retailers urge consumers not to remove the orange tip as it is used to help distinguish them from a real firearm.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The orange tip serves many purposes, one of them being for law enforcement to help discern airsoft guns from real firearms and thus prevent unnecessary excessive forces.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The minimum safe level of gear required to participate in most games includes a pair of ANSI Z87.1 eye protection, preferably a fully sealed APEL-rated ballistic eyewear.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Traditional prescription glasses and sunglasses, or goggles not rated sufficiently for impact-resistance, may shatter and/or be perforated upon being struck when used for airsoft or paintball, causing injury to the eye.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Masks, face shields and other types of full-face coverings such as balaclavas are recommended at most airsoft fields.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Rules such as a maximum muzzle velocity and engagement distance guidelines are used by different groups.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Some organizations have created common safety rules and guidelines.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Most minimum engagement distances are 10 feet (3.0 m).
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] When not actively playing, some fields require "barrel bags", also known as barrel socks, barrel condoms, barrel blockers, or barrel sleeves, to be placed over the muzzle of the gun.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The magazine is usually removed as well, and the gun fired to clear the chamber.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Most fields also require players to leave their guns set to the safety position when they are not shooting, a practice common when using real firearms.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] In certain countries, such as the Philippines, additional special rules have been adopted.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Airsoft is legal in most parts of the world.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Some countries have specific restrictions, such as maximum muzzle velocity and "unrealistic" coloring to distinguish them from actual firearms.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] They are legal throughout the United States, but restrictions do exist in cities like Chicago and Detroit.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The states of New Mexico, New York and New Jersey, however, do not allow airsoft guns to be used or handled publicly because of the resemblance to real firearms.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] They may be used on private property with the consent of the owner.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Customs and Border Protection FAQ page states that Airsoft guns are considered look-alike firearms which require the special blaze orange marking.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] In Ireland, Airsoft guns are classified as Realistic Imitation Firearms but not restricted as much as in the United Kingdom.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Under the Criminal Justice Act of 2006, Airsoft guns are legal in the Republic.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] One can buy, sell and import Airsoft guns without notifying relevant law enforcement authorities.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] They do not need to be painted in fluorescent colours, they do not need to have an orange tip, but they cannot launch the projectile with a kinetic energy exceeding 1 joule.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] However, carrying an imitation firearm in public is prohibited, and a gun carry case is required, as for real firearms.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Airsoft shops are spread over the country, and buyers must be aged 18 or over to purchase an airsoft gun.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] There is no age limit on Airsoft, as long as a minor has an adult's permission.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] In the United Kingdom, most Airsoft guns are classified as realistic imitation firearms or RIFs.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The sale, manufacture, or importation (but not gifting) of these is illegal under the Violent Crime Reduction Act 2006.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] A defence is allowed for selling for specific purposes including airsoft skirmishing.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The minimum age for buying any imitation firearm in the UK is 18.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] It is an offence to possess an imitation firearm in a public place without a reasonable excuse, for example traveling to, or from, or being at an airsoft skirmish site.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Most UK airsoft sites and retailers participate in the United Kingdom Airsoft Retailer Association Ltd (UKARA) registration scheme.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] A player who has participated in at least 3 skirmishes over a period of at least 56 days at the same skirmish site can be registered by that site.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Retailers have access to the database to verify that the purchaser can provide them with a defence.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The Border Agency also has access to check legality of imports.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] As an alternative to RIFs, IFs (Imitation Firearms, including 'two tones') are available in the UK.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] These are RIFs which have been painted a bright colour (excluding white/silver/gold) over at least 51% of the item.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] No specific defence is required for selling an IF, although the minimum age for purchasing remains 18.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] In Canada, there are laws pertaining to airsoft importing.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] All airsoft guns that are bought in Canada are legal, but when importing it, the gun has to have between 366FPS and 500FPS to pass inspection at customs, otherwise the gun will be shipped back or destroyed.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Airsoft guns in the United States are sold with a federally mandated orange tip which must be 1/4 inch or longer covering the muzzle of the replica.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Airsoft technology is used in military training and law enforcement training.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Due to airsoft's realism, relatively safe projectiles, and economical ammunition, it is well-suited to war games and force-on-force scenarios to train and improve troop's tactical proficiency via associative learning and stress inoculation.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Multiple airsoft inventions were developed originally for military and law enforcement use.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Marking rounds were invented by Kerry T.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Bowden to allow trainees to see where each projectile landed.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Much like paintball and simunitions, these marking pellets would break upon impact, marking the target with luminescent liquid.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Unlike traditional plastic pellets, marking rounds are heavier to ensure breakage of the shell on impact.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The weight can be adjusted by adding heavier liquid.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Marking rounds are critical for trainees because they allow the shooter to see exactly where they hit the target.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] This allows them to extrapolate their mistakes and improve their aim.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Reusable grenades were improved by Scott Frank to emulate the fragmentation of a real grenade in war games and scenarios.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The grenade can be loaded with paint or pellets.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] It uses a quick release of highly pressurized gas to break the shell and quickly disperse pellets or paint in all directions.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Frank's grenade, although not the first, aimed to be as realistic and predictable as an actual grenade.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] He developed a more accurate timing mechanism and secondary safety mechanisms to prevent accidental discharge.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Both marking rounds and reusable grenades gave airsoft the edge it needed to enter into military and law enforcement training grounds.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The airsoft guns used for training differ from civilian models.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Guns manufactured for professional training are made to replicate the weight, feel and the sound of its real steel counterpart.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] In general, professional training airsoft guns are GBB models and enhanced with a weighted blowback mechanism to increase the force of the kick.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Some are AEGs and are built with a blowback mechanism.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] They are also outfitted with muzzle protectors that amplify the sound to a decibel level comparable to that of a real firearm.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] The average FPS for professional training airsoft guns is higher than civilian models.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Economically, airsoft is cheaper than simulation training.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Benjamin Kratz, Fort Jackson's battalion executive officer, said that one blank M16 round can cost as much as 32 airsoft rounds.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] Airsoft can also be used in military simulations such as in malls or prisons to add to the immersion.
[src:16-inch-softball/airsoft] There are different event producers like MiR Tactical holding these events.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] USA Softball was founded in 1933 as the Amateur Softball Association (ASA) with a tournament held in Chicago that was organized by Leo Fischer and Michael J.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] The following year, the 1934 National Recreation Congress recognized the ASA.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] Shortly afterward, the ASA was located in Newark, New Jersey.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] A world amateur softball tournament was held by the ASA at Chicago's Soldier Field on September 7, 1939.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] The ASA relocated to its new headquarters in Oklahoma City on January 1, 1966.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] The ASA sponsored the highest level of college softball competition from the disbandment of the Association for Intercollegiate Athletics for Women in 1982 until the NCAA started sanctioning the sport in 1985.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] The University of South Florida won the National Championship in both years under the ASA.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] On June 30, 2016, the Amateur Softball Association of ASA/USA Softball announced that it would be changing its organizational and trade name to "USA Softball", effective on January 1, 2017, along with a new logo.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] Since 2005, the organization has run the World Cup of Softball, now known as the USA Softball International Cup.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] Devon Park also hosts the NCAA Women's College World Series and the Big 12 Conference softball championship.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] In 1978, the United States Olympic Committee named USA Softball the national governing body of softball in the United States.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] Due to this designation, USA Softball is responsible for training, equipping, and promoting the six USA softball national teams that compete in events such as the Olympics, Pan American Games, World Championships and other international and domestic events.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] Softball became an Olympic sport for the first time at the 1996 Summer Olympics in Atlanta.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] The team won the gold medal and remained in the Olympics until 2008.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] In the 2020 Olympics held in Tokyo, the USA Softball team returned to play, and placed in second place, winning the silver medal.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] Team USA has 15 players and 3 replacement players currently on the roster.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] USA Softball registers over 120,000 softball teams adding up to about 2 million players.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] USA Softball is a not-for-profit organization.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] The USA softball youth program began in 1974.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] Over 80,000 teams, 1.3 million players, and 300,000 coaches participate in USA Softball's youth division on an annual basis.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] The USA Softball adult program began in 1934.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] With over 170,000 teams, 2.5 million players, and 500,000 coaches involved on an annual basis, the adult program is the largest USA Softball program.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] USA Softball provides programs of competition for adults including fast pitch, slow pitch, and modified pitch for men and women.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] The National Softball Hall of Fame was dedicated May 26, 1973, in Oklahoma City.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] It is located at Devon Park and is open to the public.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] It has 337 members, including players, managers, umpires, and other suitable individuals.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] USA Softball publishes an updated rule book for softball each year which is widely used by adult and youth recreational leagues in the United States and abroad.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] The USA Softball rules were also used for the softball competition when it was an Olympic sport between 1996 and 2008.
[src:16-inch-softball/amateur-softball-association] The most recent Olympics to feature softball, the 2020 Summer Olympics, held in 2021, used the virtually identical WBSC ruleset.
[src:16-inch-softball/american-flag-rugby] American flag rugby is divided up among four different levels based upon the grade level a child is entering.
[src:16-inch-softball/american-flag-rugby] Each division itself has a unique set of rules in recognition that there will be different ability levels between the various age groups.
[src:16-inch-softball/american-flag-rugby] The game, while based on rugby union, is actually far more related to rugby sevens.
[src:16-inch-softball/american-flag-rugby] Similarities are seen with the number of players on the field and the arrangement of the line-outs, scrums and kick-offs.
[src:16-inch-softball/american-flag-rugby] Like rugby union, games are played in halves but the halves are significantly reduced.
[src:16-inch-softball/american-flag-rugby] The halves are the same for all four levels at 10 minutes each instead of 40 minutes each.
[src:16-inch-softball/american-flag-rugby] The rule differences between each division are minor and gradually shift closer towards rugby union rules as the child advances up in divisions and increases his or her skill set.
[src:16-inch-softball/american-flag-rugby] For Owls the game typically revolves around teaching the children to run with the ball, learning to touch the ball down when scoring a try and learning basic passing skills.
[src:16-inch-softball/american-flag-rugby] Nothing is contested, there is no kicking, and there are no conversions.
[src:16-inch-softball/american-flag-rugby] However, when children reach the Eagle level, many of the prior mentioned restrictions are removed and the children play with contest are allowed open field kicking, and the game has a more dynamic flow to it.
[src:16-inch-softball/american-flag-rugby] The first iteration of American flag rugby was founded by Tom Feury in 1998.
[src:16-inch-softball/american-flag-rugby] Feury was initially looking for nothing more than a way to get his children and their friends introduced to the game.
[src:16-inch-softball/american-flag-rugby] In 1999, the town of Denville granted him access to a field in order to do so.
[src:16-inch-softball/american-flag-rugby] The first year began with only one team and 28 children.
